08415nam a22019215i 9780691206028DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912060287 a10.1515/97806912060282doi  a(DE-B1597)635439  a(OCoLC)1350571304  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPR1868.W593bT87 2023 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a821/.1223/eng/202206081 aTurner, Marion, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Wife of Bath :bA Biography /cMarion Turner. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2023] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b14 color illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPART I Medieval Wives of Bath: Ordinary Women and English Literature -- tPROLOGUE ‘Beaten for a Book’: Literary Form and Lived Experience -- tCHAPTER 1 The Invention of Character -- tCHAPTER 2 Working Women -- tCHAPTER 3 The Marriage Market -- tCHAPTER 4 The Female Storyteller -- tCHAPTER 5 The Wandering Woman -- tPART II Alison’s Afterlife, 1400–2021 -- tPROLOGUE ‘Now Merrier and Extra Mature’ -- tCHAPTER 6 Silencing Alison -- tCHAPTER 7 When Shakespeare Met Alison -- tCHAPTER 8 Alison Abroad -- tCHAPTER 9 Alison and the Novel -- tCHAPTER 10 Black Alisons: Wives of Brixton, Bafa, and Willesden -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the award-winning biographer of Chaucer, the story of his most popular and scandalous character, from the Middle Ages to #MeTooEver since her triumphant debut in Chaucer’s Canterbury Tales, the Wife of Bath, arguably the first ordinary and recognisably real woman in English literature, has obsessed readers—from Shakespeare to James Joyce, Voltaire to Pasolini, Dryden to Zadie Smith. Few literary characters have led such colourful lives or matched her influence or capacity for reinvention in poetry, drama, fiction, and film. In The Wife of Bath, Marion Turner tells the fascinating story of where Chaucer’s favourite character came from, how she related to real medieval women, and where her many travels have taken her since the fourteenth century, from Falstaff and Molly Bloom to #MeToo and Black Lives Matter.A sexually active and funny working woman, the Wife of Bath, also known as Alison, talks explicitly about sexual pleasure. She is also a victim of domestic abuse who tells a story of rape and redemption. Formed from misogynist sources, she plays with stereotypes. Turner sets Alison’s fictional story alongside the lives of real medieval women—from a maid who travelled around Europe, abandoned her employer, and forged a new career in Rome to a duchess who married her fourth husband, a teenager, when she was sixty-five. Turner also tells the incredible story of Alison’s post-medieval life, from seventeenth-century ballads and Polish communist pop art to her reclamation by postcolonial Black British women writers.Entertaining and enlightening, funny and provocative, The Wife of Bath is a one-of-a-kind history of a literary and feminist icon who continues to capture the imagination of readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWife of Bath (Fictitious character). 0aWomen in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aAffair.  aAlice Perrers.  aAncrene Wisse.  aAnne Barton.  aArt film.  aAuthor.  aBarbara Newman.  aBecky Sharp.  aBeith (letter).  aBernardine Evaristo.  aBlanche of Lancaster.  aBrothel.  aCandide.  aCarolyn Dinshaw.  aCecily of York.  aCharivari.  aChelsea Manning.  aChristine de Pizan.  aClare Perkins.  aConcubinage.  aConfessio Amantis.  aCourtesan.  aC